1. Centre for Water Systems, College of Engineering, Mathematics and Physical Sciences, University of Exeter, Exeter, UK 2. Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, Imperial College London, London, UK {*}corresponding author(s): Simon Moulds (s.moulds@exeter.ac.uk)

\begin{abstract}
  India's green revolution has resulted in large-scale agricultural intensification to meet a growing demand for food. Irrigation has been central to this transformation, providing a buffer against the variability of the South Asian monsoon and allowing farmers to grow crops in the dry winter season. Historical datasets showing the change in irrigated area over time are necessary for assessments of global and regional change. Here, district-level inventory data showing the area of specific crop types are spatially disaggregated using various spatial input datasets, including maps of irrigated area, cropland fraction and biophysical crop suitability. The resulting dataset has a spatial resolution of 5 arcminutes $\times$ 5 arcminutes and provides a map for each crop type on an annual basis between 1970--2010, divided between rainfed and irrigated fractions and between major growing seasons. The maps show good agreement with existing contemporary maps of crop area. However, there are no equivalent datasets providing maps before the year 2000 available for comparison. The dataset is associated with considerable uncertainty at the grid cell scale arising from the district-level inventory data as well as the spatial disaggregation procedure. Consequently, we argue the dataset should be used for applications at the global and regional level rather than local-scale studies which are sensitive to the values of individual grid cells.
