India's green revolution, initiated in the mid-1960s to achieve food security for the country's rapidly growing population \cite{singh_environmental_2000}, has driven large scale land use and land management change from natural land cover and low-intensity cropland to high-input agricultural systems \cite{evenson_assessing_2003,foley_solutions_2011}. While the green revolution has enabled the country to become self sufficient in food production and supported the livelihoods of millions \cite{wada_multimodel_2013}, it has also caused a dramatic increase in the exploitation of natural resources \cite{rodell_satellite-based_2009,gleeson_water_2012}, which is expected to intensify as the country experiences major social and economic change \cite{zhao_land_2006,james_indias_2011,elliott_constraints_2014}. Spatio-temporal datasets showing the change in extent and distribution of rainfed and irrigated area over time are necessary to quantify the environmental impacts of large-scale agricultural intensification \cite{wisser_global_2008,nazemi_inclusion_2015,siebert_global_2015}. Such analyses provide insight into the drivers of change, highlight areas of unsustainable exploitation of resources and improve projections of future irrigation requirements \cite{doll_global_2002,wisser_global_2008}. \\

Several datasets of contemporary irrigated and rainfed cropland have been developed at global and regional scales. The Global Irrigated Area Mapping project (GIAM) produced a global map of irrigated area with a 5 arcminutes $\times$ 5 arcminutes spatial resolution around the year 2000 based on various data sources including Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer products and the Syst\`{e}me pour l'Observation de la Terra Vegetation (SPOT VGT) product. Separate maps based on Moderate Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer (MODIS) data with a 500m resolution were produced for the Indo-Gangetic Plain \cite{thenkabail_ganges_2005}, the Krishna basin in the Indian peninsula \cite{biggs_irrigated_2006} and the entire Indian subcontinent \cite{dheeravath_irrigated_2010}. Data products derived from remote sensing have a high spatial resolution and the use of multitemporal satellite imagery enables the detection of environmental change \cite{portmann_mirca2000-global_2010}. However, remote sensing approaches have a number of important limitations for spatio-temporal irrigated area mapping. Current classification algorithms cannot reliably distinguish between specific crop types or between irrigated and rainfed crops \cite{portmann_mirca2000-global_2010}. The fact that remotely sensed data only specifies the dominant land use/land cover class introduces a large amount of uncertainty to the resulting maps \cite{dheeravath_irrigated_2010}. Classification algorithms, which must be trained on a large number of ground truth points, are also subject to uncertainty \cite{portmann_mirca2000-global_2010}. Moreover, using satellite data for land use/land cover mapping for historical periods is challenging because of poor data availability as a result of operational decisions taken during satellite programmes \cite{wulder_global_2016}, spatial and temporal inconsistencies in satellite images \cite{verburg_challenges_2011} and persistent cloud cover during the monsoon season \cite{ju_availability_2008}.\\

An alternative strategy is to use national and subnational agricultural census data \cite{monfreda_farming_2008}. The Global Map of Irrigated Area (GMIA) \cite{siebert_development_2005}, which shows the area equipped for irrigation (AEI) around the year 2005, was produced by downscaling national and subnational inventory data about the area equipped for irrigation and maps of cropland extent. It was extended by \cite{siebert_global_2015} to show AEI between 1900 and 2005 with decadal time steps. However, the maps do not distinguish between crop types and provide the area equipped for irrigation rather than the area actually irrigated. In contrast, the Monthly Irrigated and Rainfed Crop Areas around the year 2000 (MIRCA2000) dataset \cite{portmann_mirca2000-global_2010} provides monthly grids showing rainfed and irrigated areas of 26 crops at 5 arcminute $\times$ 5 arcminute resolution. The temporal disaggregation of crop areas to monthly grids is not based on specific data about the area of crops grown in each growing season but rather based on assumed cropping intensities from \cite{monfreda_farming_2008} and regional data about the cropping periods of irrigated crops \cite{portmann_mirca2000-global_2010}. Some researchers have extrapolated MIRCA2000 back and forwards in time using country-level crop statistics, supplying the resulting spatio-temoporal dataset in impact assessment models \cite{wada_nonsustainable_2012,dalin_groundwater_2017}. Another dataset showing the spatial distribution of irrigated crops is the MapSPAM product \cite{you_generating_2014}, which downscales national and subnational data for the year 2005 using a cross-entropy optimisation technique. However, these maps neither show the growing season of individual crops, nor provide data for years other than 2005. \\

As we have shown, there is a critical shortage of spatially-explicit datasets which show changes in area of rainfed and irrigated crops over time. Moreover, existing datasets of crop area such as MIRCA2000 and MapSPAM have important limitations to do with the temporal disaggregation of crop areas between growing seasons. In this paper, we describe a new set of maps showing the rainfed and irrigated area of 33 crops on a seasonal basis between 1970--2010 at a spatial resolution of 5 arcminutes $\times$ 5 arcminutes. \\

