\section*{Methods}

\subsection*{Study area}
The Indian agricultural sector supports the livelihoods of more than 60\% of India's working population and accounts for approximately 70\% of the country's exports \cite{gadgil_indian_2006}. There are two main growing seasons in India: the \textit{kharif} season between June and October, coinciding with the South Asian monsoon, and the \textit{rabi} between October and April \cite{smilovic_limits_2015}. In some parts of India an additional growing season is possible between \textit{rabi} and \textit{kharif} \cite{thenkabail_ganges_2005}. At the country level, the main \textit{kharif} crop is rice and the main \textit{rabi} crop is wheat, although different crops are locally important. Irrigation is mainly practiced during the dry \textit{rabi} season but may also be used during the \textit{kharif} season to supplement weak monsoon rainfall and provide a buffer against intraseasonal monsoon variability. \\

\subsection*{Preparing a spatial database of sub-national agricultural inventory data}

\subsubsection*{Input data}

Indian agricultural inventory data shows the are area and production of multiple crop types as well as the proportion of each crop type that receives irrigation during a given year. The collection of agricultural data is decentralised and data collection methods vary between India's various States and Union Territories (territories administered by the Central Government). These can be separated into three broad groups: %

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textit{States and Union Territories which been cadastrally surveyed.} In this case village revenue agencies survey all fields during each growing season to compile crop and irrigation inventory data;
\item \textit{The States of Kerala, Orissa and West Bengal.} Villages in these States do not have their own revenue agency and statistics are collected from a random sample of 20\% of villages, such that over a five year period each village is surveyed once, and extrapolated to all villages
\item \textit{States and Union Territories without a formal reporting system.} In this case inventory data are based on estimates made at the village level
\end{enumerate}

