\subsubsection*{Data preparation}
In the first instance we performed data quality control on the district-level inventory dataset to remove noise from the time series data. The main data quality problems we encountered in the dataset were time series labelled as one crop type but actually belonging to another, data points labelled with the wrong area units, outliers and missing data points. These were identified by plotting the time series data of each crop type under consideration for each district unit. Mislabelled time series, to the extent that they could be identified, were changed to the correct crop type. Where possible missing data points were infilled using the ICRISAT dataset; otherwise they were infilled using a combination of linear interpolation or, if data points were missing from the start or end of the time series, last observation carried forwards. Outliers were removed and treated as missing data points. \\

For the recent period (2000--2010) it was possible to use district-level inventory data for every district and crop combination. However, as a result of reduced quality and availability of data prior to 2000 it was necessary to use a combination of subnational and national data for the historical period. Combining Indiastat and ICRISAT datasets yielded district-level data for 19 states and 16 crop types, which together represent around XY\% of India's total crop production during the historical period. Missing data was infilled using the difference between the aggregated district-level data and the country-level data from FAOSTAT. The resulting time series was apportioned between district units and irrigated and rainfed fractions using the relevant crop maps for 2005 when these became available. Similarly, since inventory data for the historical period does not provide information on the fraction of irrigated and rainfed in each growing season, we used the seasonal fraction from the corresponding base maps to disaggregate historical data to specific growing seasons. Figure~\ref{fig:study_area} shows the district boundaries used in the analysis for the two time periods, with stippling indicating the regions where FAOSTAT data was used for all crops. \\

