\subsection*{Spatial downscaling}

\subsubsection*{Input data to the downscaling routine}
Maps defining cropland extent were obtained from a new land use/land cover change dataset providing annual land cover maps for India between 1960--2010 \cite{moulds_spatiotemporal_2018}. Maps of showing the maximum attainable yield under prevailing soil, terrain and climatic conditions during 1961--1990 were obtained from the FAO Global Agro-Ecological Zones (GAEZ) database, version 3.0. Table~\ref{table:gaez_crop} provides a list of crop types included in the analysis and the corresponding potential yield map. A map of contemporary market accessibility was obtained from \cite{weiss_global_2018}. Maps of irrigated area for recent and historical periods were obtained from \cite{ambika_remotely_2016} and \cite{siebert_global_2015}, respectively. Where necessary, the input maps were aggregated to a spatial resolution of 5 arcminutes $\times$ 5 arcminutes. \\

Vector maps showing administrative boundaries for historical and recent periods were converted to raster images with the same spatial resolution as the other spatial data layers. We calculated the fractional membership of pixels to each district unit in the respective time periods, such that pixels entirely within the boundary have a value of one while pixels which intersect boundaries have values between zero and one. The resulting series of maps were used to define the grid cells to which the district level inventory data were apportioned during the disaggregation procedure. \\

