\subsection*{Spatial allocation}
The spatial allocation procedure is divided into two parts. First, we establish a set of base maps for the year 2005 using a cross-entropy optimization method. Using these maps we complete the subnational database for the historical period, as described above. We then use the maps as the main input to spatially disaggregate rainfed and irrigated crop areas from the subnational database for the other years in the study period.

\subsubsection*{Method to create base maps}
Following \cite{you_generating_2014}, we adopt a cross entropy approach to allocate sub-national crop area estimates to a spatial grid. The notion of cross entropy derives from the concept of information entropy first put forward in seminal work by Claude Shannon \cite{shannon_mathematical_1948}. According to Shannon's definition, entropy is the weighted sum of information about a random variable that is contained in its probability distribution $p_{i}, i=1,2, ...,n$, expressed:

\begin{equation}
  H(p) = - \sum_{i=1}^{n} p_{i} \ln p_{i}
\end{equation}

\noindent where convention dictates that $\ln 0 = 0$, such that a probability of zero provides no information. Cross entropy measures the difference in information content between the posterior distribution $p_{i}$ and its prior $q_{i}$, as follows:

\begin{equation}
  CE(p,q) = \sum_{i=1}^{n}p_{i} \ln (p_{i} / q_{i}) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} p_{i} \ln p_{i} - \sum_{i=1}^{n} p_{i} \ln q_{i}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $CE(p,q)$ is the cross-entropy of $p$ with respect to $q$. \\

Cross-entropy is an appropriate technique for the spatial allocation of crop areas because it effectively draws together various disparate and incomplete data sources which either constrain the likelihood or suggest the presence of a crop type in a particular location \cite{you_generating_2014}. We formulate the spatial allocation model as a cross entropy minimization problem. The posterior probability distribution is the area share, $s$, allocated to pixel $i$, crop $j$, water source $l$, such that

\begin{equation}
  s_{ijl} = \frac{A_{ijl}}{CropArea_{jl}}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $A_{ijl}$ is the allocated area in pixel $i$ of crop $j$ with water source $l$, and $CropArea_{jl}$ is the corresponding total area within the district unit according to the sub-national database. With this in mind, the spatial allocation model can be written:

\begin{equation} \label{eq:objfun}
  \begin{aligned}
  & \underset{\scriptscriptstyle{\{s_{ijl}\}}}{\text{Minimize}} \qquad CE(s,\pi) = \sum_{i}\sum_{j}\sum_{l}s_{ijl} \ln s_{ijl} - \sum_{i}\sum_{j}\sum_{l}s_{ijl} \ln \pi_{ijl}\\
  & \text{Subject to:}\\
  & \sum_{i} s_{ijl} = 1 \qquad \forall j \forall l\\
  & \sum_{j}\sum_{l} CropArea_{jl} \times s_{ijl} = Avail_{i} \qquad \forall i\\
  & \sum_{j}\sum_{l \epsilon L} CropArea_{jl} \times s_{ijl} = IrrArea_{i} \qquad \forall i\\
  \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\pi_{ijl}$ is the prior area share, $Avail_{i}$ and $IrrArea_{i}$ are respectively the total cropland and total area irrigated in pixel $i$ and $L$ is the set of irrigated crops in the district unit. The objective function (Equation~\ref{eq:objfun}) minimises the cross entropy between the estimated area shares, $s_{ijl}$ and the prior estimates, $\pi_{ijl}$. In other words, the objective of the spatial allocation model is to minimize the amount of extraneous information imposed upon the prior estimates in order to meet the model constraints. \\

It is clear that the success of the model is highly dependent upon an accurate prior distribution, $\pi_{ijl}$ \cite{you_generating_2009}. We base the estimation of prior area shares on the revenue model proposed by \cite{you_generating_2014}, which is expressed as

\begin{equation}
Rev_{ijl} = Price_{j} \times Access_{ij} \times PotYield_{ijl} \times Suitable_{ijl}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $Rev$ is revenue, $Access$ is market accessibility, $PotYield$ is potential yield and $Suitable_{ijl}$ is binary variable which indicates whether pixel $i$ is suited to crop $j$ and water source $l$. The prior area allocation $\bar{A}_{ijk}$ of a given crop is then given by:

\begin{equation} \label{eq:priorarea}
  \bar{A}_{ijl} = CropArea_{jl} \times \frac{Rev_{ijl}}{\sum\limits_{i}Rev_{ijl}} \qquad \forall i \forall j \forall l
\end{equation}

\noindent The prior area share is thus:

\begin{equation}
  \pi_{ijl} = \frac{\bar{A}_{ijl}}{\sum\limits_{i}\bar{A}_{ijl}}
\end{equation}

The implementation of the spatial allocation algorithm is adapted from the General Purpose Cross Entropy Matrix Adjustment (GPCEMA) program \cite{lemelin_gpcema_2009}. The original program seeks to adjust a prior matrix such that the sum of rows and columns in the resulting posterior matrix equal a set of marginal totals. In GPCEMA, cross-entropy is used as a measure of the extent to which the adjusted matrix diverges from the prior matrix. In our case, the prior matrix contains the estimated area of concurrently grown irrigated and rainfed crops such that matrix rows correspond to individual grid cells and columns refer to unique crop type and water supply combinations (e.g. irrigated and rainfed rice are treated separately). We adapted these constraints to those outlined in Equation~\ref{eq:objfun}. To solve the model we use the General Algebraic Modeling System with the CONOPT solver.

\subsubsection*{Method to create maps for recent and historical periods}
% For the recent period (2000--2010) we use subnational inventory data associated with the same district units as were used to construct the 2005 base maps. For the historical period (1970--1999) we use a combination of subnational and national data to overcome the reduced data quality and availability during these years. Combining Indiastat and ICRISAT datasets yielded district-level data for 19 states and 16 crop types, together supplying XY\% of India's total crop production during the historical period \cite{}. Missing data was infilled using country-level data from FAOSTAT, apportioned between district units and irrigated and rainfed fractions based on the 2005 base maps. Similarly, since inventory data for the historical period (1970-2000) does not provide information on the fraction of irrigated and rainfed in each growing season we used the seasonal fraction from the corresponding base maps to disaggregate historical data to growing season. Because the district boundaries for the historical and recent periods are not the same, we used the average fraction of all cells within the respective historical district polygon. \\

We used the 2005 maps as the basis for disaggregating inventory data for the historical and recent period. In essence, pixel values from the base maps for the respective district units replace $Rev$ in Equation~\ref{eq:priorarea}, so that the relative spatial distribution of the prior area allocation of the particular crop and year under consideration is consistent with that of the 2005 map. We perform the optimisation in the same way as for the 2005 maps, but use cropland and irrigated area constraints appropriate for the time period in question. \\

