\section*{Usage Notes}

IndiaCropAtlas provides a set of maps showing the area of rainfed and irrigated crops at 5 arcminute $\times$ 5 arcminute resolution. A set of maps is included for each year between 1970--2010, at either a seasonal or monthly temporal resolution. A set of base maps were created for 2005 using a cross-entropy optimisation method which combined district-level inventory data with various spatially explicit data sources pertaining to the spatial distribution of crops. The base maps were subsequently used to downscale district and national-level inventory data for subsequent years. The dataset has not been validated at the pixel level due to a lack of appropriate data. Crop area maps from the contemporary period (2000--2010) are consistent with district-level inventory data specifying the total area of each crop divided between irrigated and rainfed and the various seasons in which it is grown. Maps belonging to the historical period (1970--2000) are consistent with inventory data specifying rainfed and irrigated crop area. However, since the inventory data for the historical period does not divide crop area between growing areas, we divided the total irrigated and rainfed crop areas between seasons on the basis of proportions from the 2005 base maps. Both contemporary and historical maps comply with estimates of cropland extent \cite{moulds2018}. In the contemporary period maps of irrigated crops comply with a time series of remote-sensing based irrigated area maps \cite{ambika_remotely_2016}, while historical maps are consistent with a spatio-temporal database of area equipped for irrigation \cite{siebert_global_2015}. Given the lack of validation at the pixel level, we recommend that the dataset is used in regional applications rather than local analyses which are sensitive to the value of individual pixels. \\

The primary purpose of the dataset is to constrain regional and global impact assessment models to quantify and understand the environmental consequences of agricultural intensification in India. In addition, the methodology we outline may be used as a template for constructing similar datasets for other regions. There are a number of ways in which the dataset could be improved. % We have chosen here to use RiceAtlas dataset \cite{laborte_riceatlas_2017} for comparison, but it would also be possible to integrate the crop calendar maps from this dataset to augment the crop calendars we currently use to derive the monthly maps. Currently, the dataset incoporates the XYZ dataset showing the spatial distribution of rice. 
At present, remote-sensing datasets showing the spatial distribution of specific crops, other than rice, at regional scales are scarce, due to limitations associated with satellite data and processing algorithms \cite{ref}. However, as technology improves it may become possible to incorporate additional remote sensing based datasets in the spatial allocation routine. \\

Individual maps are provided as GeoTIFF files in latitude/longitude (i.e. unprojected) format. Such files may be loaded with standard Geographical Information System (GIS) software as well as various data processing languages. Pixel values represent the area of the particular crop in hectares. Users of the dataset should be aware that projecting the maps (for example to an equal-area projection) will change the aggregate area of each crop type so that it will almost certainly no longer correspond with the inventory data. \\

